Some notes:

[quote:3045ov3c]If you have them in a list, you need a new copy of the list, so just newList = oldLIst. [/quote:3045ov3c]

Actually, no. <!-- s:) --><img src="{SMILIES_PATH}/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><!-- s:) --> That will just copy the list reference. It will be the same list referenced by two variables. One way to create a new list is to use ListCombine:

[code:3045ov3c]newList = ListCombine(NewObjectList(), oldList)[/code:3045ov3c]

[quote:3045ov3c]If you don't have them in a list, you could do it by hand. But that sounds kind of tedious, so I think this would work:

Code: Select allmyRoomList = NewObjectList()
foreach (obj, AllObjects()) {
  if (DoesInherit(obj, &quot;editor_room&quot;) = true) {
    list add (myRoomList, obj)
  }
}[/quote:3045ov3c]
Keep in mind that this will break if you ever publish your game, as all references to the &quot;editor&quot; types are stripped during the publishing process (so no objects will be in the above list in such a case). If you wished to go that route, you'd probably have to define your own room base type which will still be valid once published.

